@cpmeister Another thing I tried was placing all the reflection stuff in a separate static method. This seems to work for me, since all my actions have very simple returns (Boolean, String, etc).
    private static <T> Object invokeMethod(ThingActions actions, String name, Class<?>[] classes, Object... args) {
        if (args.length != classes.length) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Number of args and number of classes don't match");
        }
        try {
            Method m = actions.getClass().getDeclaredMethod(name, classes);
            Class<?> returnClass = m.getReturnType();
            return returnClass.cast(m.invoke(actions, args));
        } catch (NoSuchMethodException | SecurityException | IllegalAccessException | IllegalArgumentException
                | InvocationTargetException e) {
            throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Problem getting or invoking method " + name);
        }
    }

Then the static action methods would invoke it like this.
    public static boolean acknowledge(@Nullable ThingActions actions, @Nullable String ackRef, @Nullable String ackType,
            @Nullable Boolean remindMeLater) {
        if (actions == null) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("actions cannot be null");
        }
        Class<?>[] argTypes = { String.class, String.class, Boolean.class };
        return (Boolean) invokeMethod(actions, "acknowledge", argTypes, ackRef, ackType, remindMeLater);
    }

Or like this if there are no arguments.
    public static @Nullable String getAlerts(@Nullable ThingActions actions) {
        if (actions == null) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("actions cannot be null");
        }
        Class<?>[] argTypes = {};
        return (String) invokeMethod(actions, "getAlerts", argTypes);
    }

